MichaÅ‚ Wyrwa

TL;DR: Students do not think about their careers when they choose cognitive science studies. Most of them just want to gain knowledge and have not thought how to fulfill expectations they have regarding their studies. Most do not know what job they want to have in the future. Moreover, there isnâ€™t one industry that is targeted by those that do know: similar number of first year students want to pursue academic, IT, creative, and health related careers.

Details about the survey

This page presents results from survey on academic and work-related expectations of first-year students of cognitive science (CS). Data was collected in early October 2019 at Adam Mickiewicz University in PoznaÅ„.

Survey was handed out to students during the Introduction to Cognitive Science class in the first week of the academic year. Students were informed that participating is optional and that it will not influence their grades. They were also informed that they do not have to sign using their real names. Because the surveys are going to be handed back to students at the end of the winter term, they were encouraged to sign in a way that would allow them to identify their survey later on.

There were 3 questions:

  1. Co rozumiesz pod pojÄ™ciem kognitywistyki? [How do you define cognitive science?]
  2. Jakie masz oczekiwania wzglÄ™dem wybranego kierunku studiÃ³w? Od czego zaleÅ¼y, czy te oczekiwania siÄ™ speÅ‚niÄ…? [Given studies you chose, what are your expectations? What will decide if they are met?]
  3. Kim chcesz zostaÄ‡? [Who do you want to become?]

The responses on the second question are divided into two separate categories: expectations and requirements.

Data was tagged by hand.

In total, 94 students filled the survey. 70 of those left one or more questions unanswered. There were 57 women and 25 men. In 12 cases the sex could not be determined.

Dataset can be downloaded from this repo.

Results

What is cognitive science?

New students know what cognitive science in a wide sense is: a science about cognition, mind and brain. They differ, however, in their understanding of CS structure. Associating CS with psychology, for example, is almost as frequent as stating that the cognitive science is interdisciplinary. All remaining disciplinesâ€”biology, philosophy, artifical intelligence researchâ€”are relatively rarely mentioned. This suggest that first year students are in most part unaware of the interdisciplinary nature of cognitive science. Perhaps the way CS is marketed in promotional materials need to be adjusted.

What are your expectations?

Expectations grouped into categories are presented in Figure 2. For almost all students, studying has an epistemic end goal, i.e., they want to gain knowledge. Surprisingly, less people chose to study CS to help themselves find a job then to find and/or develop their passions. This indicate that motivations for choosing CS are not monetary or career-related. Moreover, together with the modest number of any other expectations, results suggest that the issue in question is not thought through by young people. What do you require to meet expectations?

To assess how many students point toward their own agency when it comes to meeting their expectations, requirement responses were divided into two groups: external and internal requirements. Results were calculated as follows:

internal_expectations <- sum(grepl("wewnÄ™trzne", data$top_level_requirements))
external_expectations <- sum(grepl("zewnÄ™trzne", data$top_level_requirements))

21 students indicated internal requirements and 15 external ones. While data seems to suggest that most students believe that their success depends predominantly on their own actions, that is a half truth at best. Students seldomly responded this question:

responded_requirements <- sum(!is.na(data$requirements))
both_internal_external <- sum(grepl("zewnÄ™trzne", data$top_level_requirements) &
                                grepl("wewnÄ™trzne",data$top_level_requirements))

Out of 29 students that did respond on this question, 8 indicated both external and internal requirements. Furthermore, 65 (69.15%) students did not respond to this question at all, which shows that most students have not thought about success factors related to their expectations. Relative to all students that responded to at least one question, only 22.34% pointed to internal requirements. In the case of external requirements the percentage was 15.96%. Who do you want to be?

14 students did not answer this question. Most of those that did does not have a desired job or even an industry. Out of those that do, most students want to pursue career in the academia. Given the variety of choices and the low number of students that explicitly expect CS studies to help them in their careers, results indicate that new students differentiate between their academic activities and future careers. Industry types and number of students interested in them are presented in Figure 3.

Conclusions

Students do not think about their careers when they choose cognitive science studies. Most of them just want to gain knowledge and have not thought how to fulfill expectations they have regarding their studies.

Most do not know what job they want to have in the future. Moreover, there isnâ€™t one industry that is targeted by those that do know: similar numbers of first year students want to pursue academic, IT, creative, and health related careers.

Results indicate that young people generally do not have their higher education years planned out. It potentially gives an opportunity to shape newcoming generation of students not only in terms of CS knowledge, but also in terms of increasing studentsâ€™ awareness about the roles they can, as CS graduates, play in the society.

The data acquired here suggest that there is no simple answer on how to make the CS curriculum better. Given the variety of studentsâ€™ dream jobs, it should be highly flexible, allowing for individual changes. For example, a more research-oriented and a more IT-oriented paths, data suggest, would be attractive for students. On the other hand, given the amount of students that do not know what do they want to do in the future, a default, recommended, path through CS studies should also be available for students, focusing on skills and knowledge useful in a wide range of jobs. Especially those that are prognosed to be in high-demand in Poland in the near future.

Data from the second and especially the third year students is needed to adjust for changes related to being closer to graduation.
